(1461, 1395791657, NULL, 1395752400, '1', 2, 4, 'D', '8-9', 'Breitling', '', '', '', 1, 3, 2, 9, 'Breitling ad on page 8-9 has roller marks on the top left part of the ad, set off in the gutter and page crease. Client has complained. Is the whole run like this?', 1, '32', 'Hi Lee,\r\n\r\nAfter reviewing all of The Australian press check copies, the set off and creasing is evident throughout the entire run.\r\n\r\nThere’s a few ways to combat the set off.\r\n1.	Open the jaw settings which will decrease the amount of pressure applied to the fold. However, there’s a very fine line. Opening the jaw setting to far, could result in the book coming free of the jaw and causing a folder jam. At speed these jams can cause lengthy delays, due to the repairs involved.  \r\n2.	Positioning and size of the advert. Obviously this would be out of SPC’s hands.      \r\n3.	Reduced ink density. Again, this is a very fine line, as reducing ink could affect the advert itself and the collect pages.\r\n\r\nThere’s also a few ways to combat creasing.\r\n1.	Folder former settings can be adjusted to allow more or less support on the webs as the book travels into the folder.\r\n2.	Increased web tensions, due to The Australian’s complex job build (two book production), the turn web can lose tension causing web to crease.  \r\nAlso, in the past all Breitling and high profile adverts were flagged with SPC production so extra focus could be placed on the production. Would it be possible for a notification email to be sent in regards to upcoming productions?\r\n\r\nRegards,\r\n\r\nIan     \r\n', 'Closed', '', '40,071', '0', '0', '0', 1, 0),
